'''Gustave García''' (February 1, 1837 &ndash; June 12, 1925) was an Italian [[baritone]] [[opera singer]] and [[singing teacher]].
==Biography== Gustave García was born on February 1, 1837 in [[Milan, Italy]], the son of [[Manuel Patricio Rodríguez García]] (1805–1906) and the soprano [[Eugénie Mayer]] (1818–1880).<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Allan Keiler]] |coauthors= |title=Marian Anderson: A Singer's Journey |year= |publisher= |page=74 |quote=Gustave Garcia was the son of Manuel Garcia the younger, the most famous singing teacher of the nineteenth century. ... | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NVi0eYa8GZgC&pg=PA74&dq=Gustave+Garcia&hl=en&ei=nYo2TIf7IIH_8AaYm_SeAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Gustave%20Garcia&f=false |isbn= }}</ref> He made his professional début as an operatic baritone in 1860 at Her Majesty's Theatre in London as [[Don Giovanni]].<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Robin May]] |coauthors= |title=A companion to the opera |year=1977 |publisher= |page= |quote= His son Gustave Garcia (1837-1925) was a baritone and teacher who sang at La Scala after making his debut in London ... | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wCelsUA2eTIC&q=Gustave+Garcia+opera&dq=Gustave+Garcia+opera&hl=en&ei=4Zw2TOiOJoL48AaviO3WAw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CFMQ6AEwCA |isbn= }}</ref> He married and had a son, baritone [[Alberto García (singer)|Alberto García]] (1875–1946).
Best known in his second career, as a teacher, in 1880 he became a professor of singing at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], where he worked till 1890. He also taught at the [[Guildhall School of Music]] from 1883 to 1910, and from 1884 at the [[Royal College of Music]] until his illness and final retirement. His pupils at the Royal College included [[Martyn Green]]. He died on June 12, 1925. ==Works == *''The Actors' Art: a Practical Treatise on Stage Declamation, Public Speaking and Deportment''. London: T. Pettitt & Co., 1882<ref>Unless otherwise indicated, this section is sourced from [[Manuel García (tenor)|Manuel García]], ''L'isola disabitata'' (edited by Teresa Radomski and James Radomski). Middleton, WI: A-R Editions, 2006, p. xxii. {{ISBN|978-0-89579-594-6}}</ref> *''The Singing Teacher's Note Book, a Short Synopsis of Voice Production for Teachers of Singing and Examination Candidates''. London: Boosey & Co., 1910. *''A guide to Solo Singing. Containing Full Instructions for Singing, with a Detailed Analysis of Some Well-Known Works and Songs''. London: Stainer, Novello, Ewer & Co., 1914
==Students== *[[Béatrice La Palme]]<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |author= |coauthors= |editor= |encyclopedia=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]] |title=Béatrice La Palme |url=http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=U1ARTU0001953 |edition=2010 |date= |year= |month= |publisher= |volume= |location= |id= |isbn= |doi= |pages= |quote=She left for London in 1895, as first winner of the Lord Strathcona scholarship to the RCM, and studied there with [[Enrique Fernandez Arbos]]. Shortly thereafter she began studying voice with Gustave Garcia and sang at an RCM concert in July 1898. ...| accessdate=2010-07-04 }}</ref>
